<TITLE> New Romanian justice minister vows to tackle graft </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BUCHAREST, Dec 17 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Romania's ruling party named a new justice minister on Monday who vowed to tackle corruption after her predecessor quit under pressure from graft allegations. The nominee, 49-year-old lawyer Norica Nicolai, said her main goal would be fighting graft in a country criticised for letting reform fizzle out since it joined the European Union in January. "A main goal is to help design a strategy to prevent graft," Nicolai told reporters. "I just want to see that laws are respected and obeyed by citizens." The ruling Liberal Party appointed Nicolai to replace Tudor Chiuariu, who stepped down ahead of a potential investigation into corruption allegations against him. The appointment still needs to be approved by the president. Chiuariu faced criticism from the public and the European Commission after he criticised anti-graft prosecutors and tried to sack a prosecutor looking into high-level corruption. Romanian authorities submitted a plan to Brussels in October on judicial reform and combating organised crime and graft. The Commission is due to publish an interim report on the issue in January. bdnews24.com/lq/2008hrs The watchdog Transparency International ranks the relatively poor Black Sea state as the EU 
